In article <jktaberCK207r.K74@netcom.com>, jktaber@netcom.com (John K. Taber) writes:
> Enough pairs for the number of bits needed for katakana transmissions.  
> The West used a 5-bit code (Baudot code, the ancestor of ASCII).  What 
> was used for katakana?

Accord to the reference I cited in my earlier followup, the Japanese
used Romaji, a Roman alphabet version of kana, using the Hepburn system.
